#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:208
msgid "PHP Version"
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Required PHP version number.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:213
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Your server is running an outdated version of PHP. Older PHP versions no "
"longer receive security patches, leaving your site exposed to known "
"vulnerabilities and reducing overall performance. <br /><br />Your website "
"requires <strong>PHP %1$s</strong> or higher."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:214
msgid ""
"Contact your hosting provider and request an upgrade to a supported PHP "
"version, or migrate to a host that offers current PHP releases."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:217
msgid "MySQL Version"
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Required MySql version number, 2: Required MyMariaDBsql version number.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:222
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Your server is running an outdated version of MySQL. Unsupported MySQL "
"versions contain known security vulnerabilities and may cause performance "
"issues. <br /><br />Your website requires minimum <strong>MySQL %1$s or "
"MariaDB %2$s</strong>."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:223
msgid ""
"Contact your hosting provider and request an upgrade to a supported MySQL "
"version, or migrate to a host that offers current database releases."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:226
msgid "WordPress Version"
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to WordPress download page, 2: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:231
#, php-format
msgid ""
"A newer version of WordPress is available. Each release includes security "
"patches and bug fixes that protect your site against newly discovered "
"threats. <br /><br />Always update to the %1$slatest stable version%2$s as "
"soon as it becomes available. You will see an update notice in your "
"WordPress dashboard when a new version is ready."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:232
msgid "There is a newer version of WordPress available ({version})."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:235
msgid "WP Debug Mode"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:239
msgid ""
"WP_DEBUG is currently enabled. While useful during development, leaving "
"debug mode active on a live site exposes error messages, file paths, and "
"internal details to visitors — information that attackers can use to "
"identify vulnerabilities."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:240
msgid ""
"Set WP_DEBUG to false in wp-config.php: <code>define('WP_DEBUG', false);</"
"code>"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:244
msgid "DB Debug Mode"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:248
msgid ""
"Database debug mode is currently enabled. On a live site, this can expose "
"database error messages containing table names, query structures, and other "
"sensitive information to visitors and potential attackers."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:249
msgid ""
"Disable database debugging on live sites. You can suppress database errors "
"by adding <code>global $wpdb; $wpdb->hide_errors();</code> in wp-config.php."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:253
msgid "Script Debug Mode"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:257
msgid ""
"SCRIPT_DEBUG is currently enabled. This forces WordPress to load unminified "
"CSS and JS files, which can reveal internal paths and debug information in "
"the frontend — giving attackers insight into your site structure."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:258
msgid ""
"Set SCRIPT_DEBUG to false in wp-config.php: <code>define('SCRIPT_DEBUG', "
"false);</code>"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:262
msgid "display_errors PHP directive"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:266
msgid ""
"The display_errors PHP directive is enabled. PHP errors displayed on the "
"frontend can reveal file paths, function names, and database details — all "
"of which help attackers map your site. Errors should be logged server-side, "
"never shown to visitors."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:267
msgid ""
"Add the following to wp-config.php: <code>ini_set('display_errors', 0);</"
"code>"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:270
msgid "Backend under SSL"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:274
msgid ""
"Your admin dashboard is not served over HTTPS. Without SSL/TLS encryption, "
"login credentials and session data are transmitted in plain text, making "
"them vulnerable to interception. <br /><br />An SSL certificate is essential "
"for securing all admin communications."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <strong> tag before "Settings", 2: Closing </strong> tag after "General", 3: Opening anchor tag to HTTPS guide article, 4: Closing anchor tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:276
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Go to %1$s > %2$s and make sure <strong>WordPress Address</strong> starts "
"with <strong>https://</strong>. %3$sRead the guide%4$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:276 controllers/SecurityCheck.php:294
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:591
msgid "General"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:279
msgid "User 'admin' or 'administrator' as Administrator"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:283
msgid ""
"An administrator account is using the default username 'admin' or "
"'administrator'. These are the first usernames attackers try during brute "
"force attacks. Since the username is half of the login credentials, using a "
"predictable one significantly reduces the effort needed to compromise your "
"site."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:284
msgid ""
"Create a new administrator account with a unique username, transfer "
"ownership of existing content, then delete the 'admin' or 'administrator' "
"account."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:288
msgid "Spammers can easily signup"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:292
msgid ""
"Public user registration is enabled. Unless your site requires it (e-"
"commerce, memberships, or guest posting), open registration invites spam "
"accounts, fake content, and potential exploitation of authenticated-user "
"vulnerabilities. <br /><br />If registration is needed, protect the form "
"with Brute Force protection."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Custom Register URL settings, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag, 4: Opening <a> tag to Brute Force settings, 5: Plugin menu name, 6: Closing </a> tag, 7: Opening <strong> tag with Settings label, 8: General label, 9: Anyone can register label with closing </strong> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:294
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Change the signup path from %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > Custom Register URL "
"%3$s then activate Brute Force on Sign up from %4$s%5$s > Brute Force > "
"Settings %6$s or uncheck the option %7$s > %8$s > %9$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:294
msgid "Anyone can register"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:298
msgid "Outdated Plugins"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:302
msgid ""
"One or more plugins have updates available. Plugin updates frequently "
"include patches for known security vulnerabilities. Attackers actively scan "
"for sites running outdated plugin versions with known exploits. <br /><br /"
">Keeping all plugins up to date is one of the most effective and simplest "
"ways to protect your site."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:303
msgid ""
"Go to Dashboard > Plugins and update all plugins to their latest versions."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:306
msgid "Abandoned Plugins Detected"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:310
msgid ""
"One or more installed plugins have not been updated by their developers in "
"over 12 months. Abandoned plugins no longer receive security patches and may "
"contain unpatched vulnerabilities that attackers can exploit."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:311
msgid ""
"Review the plugins that have not been updated recently and replace them with "
"actively maintained alternatives from the WordPress directory."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:314
msgid "Outdated Themes"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:318
msgid ""
"One or more themes have updates available. Theme updates include security "
"patches and bug fixes for known vulnerabilities. <br /><br />Even inactive "
"themes can be exploited if they contain vulnerable code, since their files "
"are still accessible on the server. Keep all installed themes up to date."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:319
msgid ""
"Go to Dashboard > Appearance and update all themes to their latest versions. "
"Remove any unused themes."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:322
msgid "Default Database Prefix"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:326
msgid ""
"Your database is using the default <strong>wp_</strong> table prefix. "
"Automated SQL injection attacks commonly target this default prefix. Using a "
"custom prefix adds an additional barrier against mass-targeted attacks that "
"assume standard WordPress table names."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Plugin name, 2: Opening <a> tag to database prefix article, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:328
#, php-format
msgid ""
"%1$s protects your website from most SQL injections, but using a custom "
"database prefix adds an extra layer of defense. %2$sLearn how to change "
"it%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:332
msgid "File Permissions"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:336
msgid ""
"One or more files or directories have overly permissive settings. Incorrect "
"file permissions can allow unauthorized users to read, modify, or execute "
"sensitive files — potentially leading to full site compromise. <br /><br /"
">Directories should typically be set to 755 and files to 644."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Plugin name, 2: Opening <a> tag to file permissions article, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:338
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Even though %1$s protects default paths after customization, we recommend "
"verifying correct permissions for all files and directories. Use File "
"Manager or FTP to review and adjust. %2$sRead the guide%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:342
msgid "Security Keys and Salts"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:346
msgid ""
"WordPress security keys and salts strengthen the encryption of data stored "
"in user cookies and hashed passwords. Without properly configured keys, "
"session tokens and passwords are easier to crack. <br /><br />Each key "
"should be unique, random, and at least 64 characters long."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:347
msgid ""
"Define all eight security constants in wp-config.php with unique, random "
"values: <code>AUTH_KEY, SECURE_AUTH_KEY, LOGGED_IN_KEY, NONCE_KEY, "
"AUTH_SALT, SECURE_AUTH_SALT, LOGGED_IN_SALT, NONCE_SALT</code>"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:351
msgid "Security Keys Need Rotation"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:355
msgid ""
"Your security keys have not been regenerated in a long time. Regularly "
"rotating security keys invalidates all existing sessions and forces re-"
"authentication, limiting the window of exposure if credentials are "
"compromised."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to WordPress secret key generator, 2: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:357
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Generate %1$snew security keys%2$s and replace the existing values in wp-"
"config.php: <code>AUTH_KEY, SECURE_AUTH_KEY, LOGGED_IN_KEY, NONCE_KEY, "
"AUTH_SALT, SECURE_AUTH_SALT, LOGGED_IN_SALT, NONCE_SALT</code>"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:361
msgid "Weak Database Password"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:365
msgid ""
"Your database password is empty or too simple. Even though most servers "
"restrict database access to localhost, a weak password provides no defense "
"if that restriction is ever bypassed or misconfigured."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:366
msgid ""
"Set a strong database password — at least 12 characters with a mix of "
"uppercase, lowercase, numbers, and special characters. Update the password "
"in wp-config.php: <code>define('DB_PASSWORD', 'NEW_DB_PASSWORD_GOES_HERE');</"
"code>"
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: wp-content path.
#. translators: 1: Admin path.
#. translators: 1: Login path.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:370 controllers/SecurityCheck.php:391
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:402
#, php-format
msgid "%1$s is visible in source code"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:374
msgid ""
"Default WordPress paths like wp-content and wp-includes are visible in your "
"source code. These paths confirm to bots and attackers that your site runs "
"WordPress, making it a target for automated exploit scanners."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Core settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:376
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Change default paths from %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > WP Core Security%3$s"
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: wp-content path.
#. translators: 1: Login path.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:380 controllers/SecurityCheck.php:413
#, php-format
msgid "%1$s path is accessible"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:384
msgid ""
"The original WordPress paths are still accessible even though custom paths "
"are set. Bots can still reach plugins and themes at their default locations, "
"bypassing the path changes. <br /><br />Hiding old paths ensures that only "
"the custom paths work, fully removing the original entry points."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Core settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:386
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Change the default path and switch on %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > Hide "
"WordPress Common Paths%3$s"
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to KB article, 2: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:396
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Your custom admin path is exposed in the page source code (typically through "
"the AJAX URL). This allows attackers to discover your admin path and launch "
"targeted brute force attacks. <br /><br />%1$sLearn how to hide the admin "
"path from source code%2$s."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to AJAX settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag, 4: Opening <strong> tag, 5: Closing </strong> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:398
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Change the default ajax path and switch on %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > Hide wp-"
"admin from ajax URL%3$s. %4$sAlso verify that no installed plugins reference "
"the admin path in frontend output.%5$s"
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to KB article, 2: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:407
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Your custom login path is exposed in the page source code. This defeats the "
"purpose of changing the login URL, as attackers can still discover it and "
"target it with brute force attacks. <br /><br />The custom login path must "
"be kept secret, and Brute Force Protection should be active. %1$sLearn how "
"to hide the login path from source code%2$s."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <strong> tag, 2: Closing </strong> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:409
#, php-format
msgid ""
"%1$sRemove the login path%2$s from any theme menus, widgets, or page content "
"that expose it in the frontend."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:417
msgid ""
"The default wp-login.php path is still accessible. Even with a custom login "
"URL configured, bots can still find and attack the original login page. "
"Blocking access to the default path forces all login traffic through your "
"custom URL, where Brute Force Protection can be applied."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Custom login URL settings, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag, 4: Opening <a> tag to Brute Force settings, 5: Plugin menu name, 6: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:419
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Set a custom login URL from %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > Custom login URL%3$s "
"and switch on %4$s%5$s > Brute Force Protection%6$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:423
msgid "wp-config.php & wp-config-sample.php are accessible"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:427
msgid ""
"Your wp-config.php file is publicly accessible. This file contains your "
"database credentials, security keys, and other critical configuration "
"details. If an attacker can read this file, they can gain full control of "
"your database and website."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Core settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:429
#, php-format
msgid "Switch on %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > Hide WordPress Common Files%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:433
msgid "readme.html file is accessible"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:437
msgid ""
"The readme.html file is publicly accessible and reveals your WordPress "
"version number. Attackers use this to identify sites running versions with "
"known vulnerabilities."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Plugin menu name, 2: Opening <a> tag to Core settings URL, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:439
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Switch on %1$s > Change Paths > Hide WordPress Common Files from %2$sHide "
"WordPress Common Paths%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:443
msgid "install.php & upgrade.php are accessible"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:447
msgid ""
"The wp-admin/install.php and wp-admin/upgrade.php files are publicly "
"accessible. These files have been associated with security vulnerabilities "
"in the past and should not be reachable on a live site."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Plugin menu name, 2: Opening <a> tag to Core settings URL, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:449
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Switch on %1$s > Change Paths > Hide WordPress Common Files from %2$sHide "
"WordPress Common Paths%3$s and select also install.php & upgrade.php"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:453
msgid "7G/8G Firewall Not Loaded"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:457
msgid ""
"The 7G/8G Firewall is not currently active. Without these rulesets, "
"malicious requests — including SQL injection attempts, script injections, "
"and exploit probes — are not filtered at the server level before they reach "
"your site."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Firewall settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:459
#, php-format
msgid "Switch on the 7G or 8G Firewall from %1$s%2$s > Firewall & Headers%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:463
msgid "Automated IP Blocking Not Active"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:467
msgid ""
"Automated IP Blocking is not currently active. Without this protection, "
"repeated suspicious requests from the same IP — such as brute force probes, "
"scanner sweeps, and exploit attempts — are not blocked automatically. This "
"increases server load and leaves your site exposed to sustained attacks that "
"cannot be addressed fast enough manually."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Firewall settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:469
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Switch on the Automated IP Blocking option from %1$s%2$s > Firewall & "
"Headers%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:473
msgid "Version Numbers Exposed"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:477
msgid ""
"WordPress, plugin, and theme version numbers are visible in your source "
"code. Attackers use version information to identify sites running software "
"with known vulnerabilities and target them with automated exploits."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Tweaks settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Feature label, 4: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:479
#, php-format
msgid "Switch on %1$s%2$s > Tweaks > %3$s%4$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:479
msgid "Hide Versions from Images, CSS and JS"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:483
msgid "PHP register_globals is on"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:487
msgid ""
"The register_globals PHP directive is enabled. This is a critical security "
"risk — it allows external input to overwrite internal PHP variables, "
"enabling attackers to manipulate your application logic. This directive has "
"been removed in modern PHP versions due to its severity."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:488
msgid ""
"Set <code>register_globals = off</code> in php.ini, or contact your hosting "
"provider to disable it immediately. Consider switching hosts if they enable "
"this by default."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:491
msgid "PHP Version Exposed"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:495
msgid ""
"Your server is broadcasting its PHP version in HTTP response headers. This "
"information helps attackers identify which PHP vulnerabilities may apply to "
"your server."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:496
msgid ""
"Set <code>expose_php = off</code> in php.ini, or contact your hosting "
"provider to disable it."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:499
msgid "PHP safe_mode is on"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:503
msgid ""
"PHP safe_mode is enabled on your server. This deprecated directive was an "
"attempt to solve shared hosting security at the PHP level but was "
"architecturally flawed and officially removed in PHP 5.4. <br /><br />When "
"enabled, it can break legitimate PHP functions while providing no real "
"protection — attackers can easily bypass its restrictions."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:504
msgid ""
"Set <code>safe_mode = off</code> in php.ini, or contact your hosting "
"provider to disable it. If your host requires safe_mode, consider migrating "
"to a modern hosting environment."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:507
msgid "PHP allow_url_include is on"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:511
msgid ""
"The allow_url_include PHP directive is enabled. This allows PHP to include "
"remote files via URLs in include/require statements, exposing your site to "
"Remote File Inclusion (RFI) attacks where attackers can execute arbitrary "
"code on your server."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:512
msgid ""
"Set <code>allow_url_include = off</code> in php.ini, or contact your hosting "
"provider to disable it. There is no legitimate use case for this directive "
"on production sites."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:515
msgid "Plugin/Theme Editor Enabled"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:519
msgid ""
"The built-in plugin and theme file editor is active. If an attacker gains "
"admin access, they can use this editor to inject malicious PHP code directly "
"into your site files — instantly compromising the entire installation "
"without needing FTP or server access."
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:520
msgid ""
"Add the following to wp-config.php to disable the file editor: "
"<code>define('DISALLOW_FILE_EDIT', true);</code>"
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Folder path.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:525
#, php-format
msgid "%1$s directory is browsable"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:529
msgid ""
"Directory browsing is enabled on your uploads folder. Anyone can view and "
"download all uploaded files by navigating to the directory URL — this is "
"both a security risk and a copyright concern."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to external directory browsing article, 2: Closing </a> tag, 3: Opening <a> tag to Core settings URL, 4: Plugin menu name, 5: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:531
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Learn how to %1$sdisable directory browsing%2$s, or switch on %3$s%4$s > "
"Change Paths > Disable Directory Browsing%5$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:535
msgid "Windows Live Writer Link Exposed"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:539
msgid ""
"The Windows Live Writer manifest link is present in your page header. This "
"is a WordPress-specific fingerprint that confirms your CMS to automated "
"scanners. Since Windows Live Writer is discontinued, there is no reason to "
"keep this enabled."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Tweaks settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:541
#, php-format
msgid "Switch on %1$s%2$s > Tweaks > Hide WLW Manifest scripts%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:545
msgid "XML-RPC Access Enabled"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:549
msgid ""
"XML-RPC is currently accessible. This protocol sends credentials in plain "
"text with every request and supports system.multicall, which allows "
"attackers to test thousands of passwords in a single HTTP request. Unless "
"you specifically need XML-RPC for remote publishing or the Jetpack plugin, "
"it should be disabled."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to API settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:551
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Disable XML-RPC from %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > Disable XML-RPC access%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:555
msgid "RSD Endpoint Exposed"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:559
msgid ""
"The Really Simple Discovery (RSD) endpoint link is visible in your page "
"header. Unless you use pingbacks or external blog clients that rely on RSD, "
"this link serves no purpose and acts as a WordPress fingerprint that "
"confirms your CMS to scanners."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to API settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:561
#, php-format
msgid "Switch on %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > Hide RSD Endpoint%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:565
msgid "Author URL Enumeration via ID"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:569
msgid ""
"Usernames can be discovered by iterating through author IDs (e.g., /?"
"author=1, /?author=2). WordPress redirects valid IDs to the author archive "
"URL, revealing the username. <br /><br />While usernames alone don't grant "
"access, they provide attackers with half the credentials needed and enable "
"targeted brute force or phishing attacks."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Author settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:571
#, php-format
msgid "Switch on %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > Hide Author ID URL%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:575
msgid "User Enumeration via REST API"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:579
msgid ""
"Usernames are discoverable through the WordPress REST API (e.g., /wp-json/wp/"
"v2/users). This endpoint can expose author IDs, display names, and author "
"slugs — which often match or closely resemble the actual login username. "
"<br /><br />Attackers use this information for targeted brute force attacks "
"and phishing campaigns."
msgstr ""

#. translators: 1: Opening <a> tag to Author settings URL, 2: Plugin menu name, 3: Closing </a> tag.
#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:581
#, php-format
msgid "Switch on %1$s%2$s > Change Paths > Hide User Enumeration%3$s"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:585
msgid "Default WordPress Tagline"
msgstr ""

#: controllers/SecurityCheck.php:589
msgid ""
"Your site is still using the default WordPress tagline \"Just another "
"WordPress site\". This is a well-known WordPress fingerprint that makes it "
"easy for bots and scanners to confirm your CMS. It also appears "
"unprofessional to visitors."
msgstr ""

